3) Data Preparation¶

  • Data preprocessing: Was ist nötig im Kontext von BERT und Transformer models?
  • NLP spezifisch
    • stopwords entfernen: Nicht unbedingt notwendig. BERT-Modelle sind in der Lage, den Kontext von Wörtern zu verstehen, sodass Stopwörter oft nicht explizit entfernt werden müssen. In einigen Fällen kann es jedoch hilfreich sein, um den Text zu vereinfachen.
    • Groß- u Kleinschreibung ignorieren: Nicht notwendig. Die meisten BERT-Modelle verwenden eine eigene Tokenisierung, die die Groß- und Kleinschreibung berücksichtigt. Modelle wie bert-base-uncased sind bereits auf Kleinschreibung trainiert.
    • Sonderzeichen ignorieren: Nicht notwendig. BERT-Tokenizer behandeln Sonderzeichen explizit und behalten sie bei, um den Kontext nicht zu verlieren.
    • Tokenisierung: Notwendig. Die BERT-Tokenisierung erfolgt durch spezialisierte Tokenizer (wie WordPiece oder SentencePiece), die den Text in Subwort-Einheiten aufteilen. Dies ist ein integraler Bestandteil der Verarbeitung mit BERT.
    • Lemmatisierung: nicht nötig wegen großem Trainingsdatensatz (Nicht notwendig. BERT verarbeitet Wörter in ihrem Kontext und die Subwort-Tokenisierung macht eine explizite Lemmatisierung überflüssig.)
  • Generell
    • NAs und Duplikate entfernen

def remove_stop_lemmatize(text):
    text = text.replace('-',' ')
    text = re.sub (r'([^a-zA-Z ]+?)', '', text)
    text = text.split(' ')
    return ' '.join(lemmatizer.lemmatize(word.lower()) for word in text if word.lower() not in stop_words)

input["corpus_clean"] = input["corpus"].apply(remove_stop_lemmatize)

def create_similarity_heatmap(corpus_embeddings):
    similarity_matrix = cosine_similarity(corpus_embeddings)
    sns.set(font_scale=1)
    f, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(11, 9))
    c = sns.heatmap(similarity_matrix, square=True,  ax=ax)
    c.set(xlabel='Document ID', ylabel='Document ID')
    plt.show()
    fig = c.get_figure()
    fig.suptitle('TF-IDF Document Similarity Matrix', fontsize=25)

6) Clustering¶

6.a) Elbow Plot¶

In [ ]:
def plot_elbow_method(embedding):
  
    Sum_of_squared_distances = []
    K = range(1,15)
    for k in K:
        km = KMeans(n_clusters=k)
        km = km.fit(embedding)
        Sum_of_squared_distances.append(km.inertia_)
    plt.plot(K, Sum_of_squared_distances, 'bx-')
    plt.xlabel('k')
    plt.ylabel('Sum_of_squared_distances')
    plt.title('Elbow Method For Optimal k')
    plt.show()

6.b) PCA and Kmeans¶

  • We do PCA reduction in order to reduce the similarity matrix to less dimensions (for plotting in two dimensions)
In [ ]:
def get_cluster_kmeans(vectorize, num_clusters, r_state=100):
    km = KMeans(n_clusters = num_clusters, random_state=r_state )
    km.fit(vectorize)
    cluster_list = km.labels_.tolist()
    return cluster_list

def pca_reduction(similarity_matrix, n_components):
    one_min_sim = 1 - similarity_matrix
    pca = PCA(n_components)
    pos = pca.fit_transform(one_min_sim)
    x_pos, y_pos = pos[:, 0], pos[:, 1]
    return (x_pos, y_pos)

def plot_graph(clusters, umap_data):
    result = pd.DataFrame(umap_data, columns=['x', 'y'])
    result['labels'] = clusters
    plt.figure(figsize=(10,10))
    sns.scatterplot(
        x="x", y="y",
        hue="labels",
        palette='Spectral',
        data=result,
        legend="full"
    )

7) Choosing the right model¶

sentence-transformers/bert-base-nli-mean-tokens:

⚠️ This model is deprecated. Please don't use it as it produces sentence embeddings of low quality. You can find recommended sentence embedding models here: SBERT.net - Pretrained Models

  • Daher werden wir eines der kleineren "Original Models" aus https://sbert.net/docs/sentence_transformer/pretrained_models.html nehmen, welches geeignet scheint (general use oder spezifisch für unsere Inhalte)

  • sollten wir mehr Deutsche und auch anderssprachige Dokumente haben, sollten wir zu einem Mulitlingual model greifen. Hier sollte die dissimilarity zu Englischen Dokumenten bereits dafür sorgen, dass sie halbwegs geeignet geclustert werden.

7.a) Initiating the model¶

#Mean Pooling - Take attention mask into account for correct averaging
def mean_pooling(model_output, attention_mask):
    token_embeddings = model_output[0] #First element of model_output contains all token embeddings
    input_mask_expanded = attention_mask.unsqueeze(-1).expand(token_embeddings.size()).float()
    sum_embeddings = torch.sum(token_embeddings * input_mask_expanded, 1)
    sum_mask = torch.clamp(input_mask_expanded.sum(1), min=1e-9)
    return sum_embeddings / sum_mask

7.c) KMeans Implementation¶

Elbow Method to estimate # of clusters¶

In [ ]:
plot_elbow_method(sentence_embeddings)
  • Elbow plot plots the WCSS (within cluster sum of squares) = squared distance between each point and the centroid in a cluster
  • as number of clusters increase, WCSS value decreases.
  • K value corresponding to the point where the plot decreases more slowly is optimal -> we have diminishing win of WCSS with more clusters.
  • The "elbow" is near 4, so we will chose 4 clusters

using BERTopic¶

Alternativer Lösungsansatz

  • BERTopic nutzt, wie wir oben, Transformers, um Embeddings zu bekommen, und Clustert danach die Embeddings mit UMAP & HDBSCAN.

  • Hier eine Beschreibung, die ich während meines Praktikums bei Yagora erstellt habe, als ich BERTopic nutzte:

  • siehe https://maartengr.github.io/BERTopic/getting_started/quickstart/quickstart.html für eine Übersicht

How BERTopic works:¶

The algorithm contains, roughly, 4 stages:

  • Extract document embeddings with Sentence Transformers (https://github.com/UKPLab/sentence-transformers) or TF-IDF

    • Sentence transformers basically transform sentences into sentence embeddings: Sentences with similar meaning are closer in vector space. Pre-trained models are used which can be fine-tuned for various use-cases.

  • Cluster document embeddings to create groups of similar documents with UMAP (https://umap-learn.readthedocs.io/en/latest/clustering.html) and HDBSCAN (https://hdbscan.readthedocs.io/en/latest/how_hdbscan_works.html)

    • These algorithms cluster the previously transformed sentences into clusters with similar meaning, resulting in clusters of topics.
    • UMAP is used to recude the dimensionality, then HCBSCAN (which suffers from the curse of dimensionality) is used to cluster similar documents.

  • Extract and reduce topics with c-TF-IDF (https://github.com/MaartenGr/cTFIDF)

    • c-TF-IDF is a class-based TF-IDF procedure that can be used to generate features from textual documents based on the class they are in.
    • Typical applications of c-TF-IDF:
      • Informative Words per Class: Which words make a class stand-out compared to all others?
      • Class Reduction: Using c-TF-IDF to reduce the number of classes
      • Semi-supervised Modeling: Predicting the class of unseen documents using only cosine similarity and c-TF-IDF

  • Improve coherence of words with Maximal Marginal Relevance (https://www.researchgate.net/publication/221614169_Creating_and_Evaluating_Multi-Document_Sentence_Extract_Summaries)

    • A text passage has high marginal relevance if it is both relevant to the query and useful for a summary, while having minimal similarity to previously selected passages.
    • This will further improve the representativity of a keyword for a topic

MMR considers the similarity of keywords/keyphrases with the document, along with the similarity of already selected keywords and keyphrases. This results in a selection of keywords that maximize their within diversity with respect to the document.

explanation of axis:

  • the algorithm takes the c_tf_idf: a matrix containing a value (importance score) for each word per topic. In the c_tf_idf, words with high values within topics are representational for the respective topic.

  • Now we normalize these "importance" values using MinMaxScaler (scales features between a given range): These will be the values of X and Y later.

  • If word x is important in topic 1, it will have a high score there. In other topics it might have a lower score. As we have many topics, we need to reduce the dimensionality here.

  • This is done by embedding the matrix into 2d using UMAP: An algorithm that is often used for visualization by reducing data to 2-dimensions. Similar to t-SNE but faster. For details in UMAP: It takes the two nearest neighbors, using the hellinger distance for probabilities.

  • Now we will have similar topics near each other: Topics where words are similar in importance are closer to each other.

  • Wir können auch auf n-gram-representations gehen (mehr als 1 wort-Tokens)

Bonus: ChatGPT implementation¶

  • Wir könnten multi aspect representations nutzen, um die Topics besser zu erfassen:

https://maartengr.github.io/BERTopic/getting_started/multiaspect/multiaspect.html

  • Hier nutze ich ChatGPT, um topics besser zu beschreiben (Ihren API Key können Sie in einer .env Datei als Variable API_KEY speichern)
In [ ]:
import openai
from bertopic.representation import OpenAI
from dotenv import load_dotenv
import os
load_dotenv()

API_KEY = os.getenv('API_KEY')

# Fine-tune topic representations with GPT
client = openai.OpenAI(api_key = API_KEY)
representation_model = OpenAI(client, model="gpt-3.5-turbo", chat=True)
topic_model = BERTopic(representation_model=representation_model, verbose = True, calculate_probabilities=True)
